lina. The stories that emerge from his research include incredible successes in mobilizing immigrant communities, including organizations that registered sixty thousand new immigrant voters in New York. They also reveal efforts to suppress nonprofit voter mobilization in Florida and describe the organizational response to hate crimes directed at immigrants in Illinois.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunity organization; United States. 0aElections; United States. 0aImmigrants; Political activity; United States. 0aImmigrants; Services for; United States. 0aNonprofit organizations; Political activity; United States. 0aPolitical participation; United States. 4aBusiness (General). 4aDiscrimination & Race Relations. 4aPolitical Science & Political History.  aimmigrants, immigrant communities, nonprofit voter mobilization, organizational response, hate crimes.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2016z9783110485332oZDB-23-DSW40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170592240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501705922423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501705922/original  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2016  aZDB-23-DSWb2016